gration theories such as neofunctionalism and the application of Habermas’s democratic theory to the EU. The second part addresses ‘cultural modernity’ in Europe - ‘Europessimism’ is argued to be a subset of the broader cultural pessimism that has assailed the project of modernity in recent decades with renewed intensity in the wake of 9/11. The final section looks at the conceptual landscape of the Constitutional Convention.The authors academia.edu page can be reached using this link http://independent.academia.edu/ShivdeepGrewal/.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional lawzEuropean Union countries. 0aEuropean cooperation. 0aEuropean federation. 0aLawzEuropexPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aConstitutional Convention.  aEuropean Constitution.  aEuropean Union.  aEuropessimism.  aGerman philosopher.  aHabermasian account.  aJürgen Habermas.  acommunicative rationality.  aconcept of juridification.  acultural pessimism.  ademocratic theory.  amodernity.  aneofunctionalism.  apolitical theory.  asocial democrats.  asocial modernity.1 aGrewal, Shivdeep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613019840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130198/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles